  "stage": {
    "id": "web3_blockchain_foundations",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Module 1: Web3 & Blockchain Foundations",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "web3_protocol",
        "title": "Web3.0 & Protocol Understanding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Web1(read) → Web2(read+write) → Web3(read+write+own) — the internet's three acts\n- Protocols replace corporate intermediaries with open cooperation mechanisms\n- Trust shifts from social contracts to code-based, verifiable contracts\n- Information and transaction costs drop to near-zero in protocol economies\n- Open-source philosophy and blockchain are deeply connected\n\n**Common Computer (2024)** Web3 OJT Chapter 1 offers a clear overview of the internet's evolutionary stages.\n\nLet's compare the history of the internet to a library. **Web1** was a read-only library — you could browse books, but couldn't write your own. **Web2** opened the doors for anyone to publish. But there's a catch: the librarian (the platform) owns every book and monopolizes the reading fees.\n\n**Web3** flips this paradigm. It's a decentralized library where authors hold direct ownership of their works and can transact with readers without intermediaries. The mechanism that makes this possible is the **protocol**.\n\nProtocols are open cooperation mechanisms that replace corporations. Previously, facilitating a transaction required a trusted third party — a bank, a platform. Blockchain protocols implement trust through code, marking the shift from social contracts to code-based contracts.\n\nThe key insight is this: Web3 is not simply a technology upgrade — it's a **revolution in ownership**. Users can directly own their data, digital assets, and even parts of internet infrastructure itself.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "dao_101",
        "title": "DAO 101: Decentralized Autonomous Organizations",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- DAO = smart contracts (rules) + governance tokens (voting power) + on-chain treasury\n- DAO vs corporation: direct democracy vs delegated hierarchy\n- Progressive decentralization: PMF first → community expansion → protocol handoff\n- Coase's transaction cost theory: blockchain minimizes costs, reducing need for firms\n- The 'blockchain person' — identity shifts from single employer to multi-DAO participation\n\n**Common Computer (2024)** Chapter 2 explores the **DAO (Decentralized Autonomous Organization)**.\n\nThe easiest analogy for a DAO is a **vending machine with no owner**. The machine runs automatically according to its rules (smart contracts), revenue flows into a shared vault (treasury), and changing the menu requires a vote from coin holders (token holders).\n\nA traditional corporation follows a top-down delegation structure: **shareholders → board → executives**. A DAO, by contrast, runs on **direct voting by token holders** — a form of direct democracy. There is no CEO; code enforces the rules.\n\nAn interesting concept is **progressive decentralization**. Going fully decentralized from day one would be chaotic, so the process unfolds in three stages: (1) achieve product-market fit while retaining admin authority, (2) expand community participation and distribute tokens, (3) hand off the protocol once sufficient decentralization is reached.\n\nAccording to Coase's transaction cost theory, when blockchain drives transaction costs toward zero, the economic rationale for internalizing activities within a firm dissolves. This is the economic argument for why DAOs can replace traditional corporate structures.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "bitcoin_ethereum",
        "title": "Bitcoin & Ethereum: The Two Pillars of Blockchain",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Bitcoin: P2P electronic cash using cryptographic proof, not trusted third parties (Satoshi, 2008)\n- Proof-of-Work: SHA-256 mining, difficulty adjustment, longest-chain rule\n- Ethereum: Turing-complete smart contracts — APPLY(S, TX) → S' state machine (Vitalik, 2014)\n- EVM and Gas: distributed virtual machine with computation cost defense\n- The Merge (2022): PoW → PoS transition, 99.95% energy reduction\n\n**Satoshi Nakamoto's (2008)** Bitcoin whitepaper starts from a single fundamental problem: \"How do we eliminate dependence on trusted third parties?\"\n\nThink of Bitcoin as **digital gold**. Physical gold derives its value from scarcity; Bitcoin guarantees value through **cryptographic proof**. Each block contains the hash of the previous block, forming a chain, and Proof-of-Work achieves consensus via the principle of \"1 CPU = 1 vote.\"\n\n**Vitalik Buterin (2014)** identified Bitcoin's limitations precisely. Bitcoin only supports simple payment scripts, but Ethereum provides a **Turing-complete** language. Ethereum operates as a global state machine: `APPLY(S, TX) → S'` — every transaction modifies the global state.\n\nThe EVM (Ethereum Virtual Machine) is a distributed virtual machine that every node in the world runs identically, and the **Gas** mechanism protects the network from malicious code. In 2022, The Merge transitioned Ethereum from PoW to PoS, reducing energy consumption by 99.95%.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
